==English==

===Etymology===
A term whose origin is generally attributed to whitewater kayakers in the Southeast United States in the mid- to late-1970s. The boof developed from an evolution of longer, slalom-style kayaks constructed of fiberglass to shorter, creek-style kayaks constructed of polyethylene. This development was significant since whitewater kayaks could now hit rocks with a much smaller likelihood of breaking. Subsequently, techniques were developed to "jump" or "ski jump" hydraulic backwash at the base of waterfalls which significantly advanced the navigability of Class IV and V rapids compared to the fiberglass era. 


The boof was made famous by the book William Nealy's ''Kayak: The Animated Manual of Intermediate and Advanced Whitewater'' (Menasha Ridge Press, 1986) and enjoys widespread use today.

===Noun===
'''boof'''

# The sound that a kayak makes when it lands on the water after "ski jumping" a rock or hydraulic in the course of navigating a river or creek.


===Adjective===
'''boof'''

# {{slang}} to the extreme or max
#: ''That jump was boof!''


===Adverb===
'''boofing'''
# {{slang}} to the extreme or max
#: ''That jump was boofing crazy!''
# {{slang}} the the most that something can be done
#: ''The winner was boofing running all out on that last leg.''


